Clean the data and map to HUGO symbols

1 - Download the data

First, I downloaded the data in GSE178521 (Hu et al., 2022). This data set have 6 samples, 3 replicates for the control (GFPkd1, GFPkd2, GFPkd3) and 3 replicates for the test condition (PRMT5kd1, PRMT5kd2, PRMT5kd3).

2 - Assess

Let’s briefly take a look at the count matrix. We have 58,825 rows (genes) in this data, and none of the gene_ids occur more than once. There are only about 20,000 - 25,000 genes in humans, but I got a lot more rows in my starting data. Based on my research, there might be some pseudo genes and non-coding genes. I am not sure whether or not that is the case here, but I will filter this data first.

I saw many rows with 0 count for all samples. I removed those rows with 0 count for at least 3 samples. Now, we only got 15159 rows left, which seems to be a good amount of genes. Using this number, the coverage of the data is about 61% - 76%.

3 - Map

Since this dataset only contains the gene IDs, I mapped the gene IDs to the HGNC symbols using biomaRt.

if (!requireNamespace("biomaRt", quietly = TRUE))
  BiocManager::install("biomaRt")

library(biomaRt)

ensembl <- useMart("ensembl")
ensembl <- useDataset("hsapiens_gene_ensembl", mart = ensembl)

#check to see if PRMT5_id_conversion file exists
conversion_stash <- "PRMT5_id_conversion.rds"
if(file.exists(conversion_stash)){
  PRMT5_id_conversion <- readRDS(conversion_stash)
} else {
  PRMT5_id_conversion <- getBM(attributes = c("ensembl_gene_id","hgnc_symbol"),
                            filters = c("ensembl_gene_id"),
                            values = count_filtered$gene_id,
                            mart = ensembl)
  saveRDS(PRMT5_id_conversion, conversion_stash)
}

4 - Clean

I chose not to remove any outliers since I think the data entries looks reasonable to me. Even though in the later section there are some entries to be negative infinity after cpm and log2 operation, I am not sure whether or not those rows should be removed, so I chose not to remove them here. In the previous step, I have removed the rows with low counts.

Normalization

I normalized the data using Trimmed Mean of M-values (TMM) normalization method in the edgeR (Robinson et al., 2010) package. TMM and Relative Log Expression (RLE) give similar results. I chose TMM since I am used to work with edgeR.

# Create an edgeR container for count data
filtered_data_matrix <- as.matrix(count_filtered_annot[,3:8])
rownames(filtered_data_matrix) <- count_filtered_annot$hgnc_symbol
d <- DGEList(counts = filtered_data_matrix, 
             group = c('GFP', 'GFP', 'GFP', 'PRMT5', 'PRMT5', 'PRMT5'))

# Calculate the normalization factors
d <- calcNormFactors(d)
normalized_counts <- cpm(d)

I plotted two box plots showing the samples before and after normalization. Before normalization, we saw that the replicates don’t variate a lot. The plots look very similar before and after normalization, but we can still see slight difference if we look carefully.

Summary: Interpret, and document

  1. What are the control and test conditions of the dataset?
  • The purpose of this RNA-seq experiment is to identify the whether inhibition of PRMT5 expression would affect the expression of certain genes related to tumorigenesis. So the test condition here is the knockdown of PRMT5 and the control is the knockdown of GFP.
  1. Why is the dataset of interest to you?
  • First, this dataset is an RNA-seq dataset with several replicates. Second, it is associated with human cancers, specifically lung cancer. I am very interested in cancer biology, so I think this dataset is very suitable for me.
  1. Were there expression values that were not unique for specific genes? How did you handle these?
  • No. There was no duplicate rows for specific genes.
  1. Were there expression values that could not be mapped to current HUGO symbols?
  • Yes, there are 34 expression values that could not be mapped to current HUGO symbols. Also, 951 values were mapped to an empty string. In total, 985 values aren’t preoperly mapped, which is about 6%.
  1. How many outliers were removed?
  • None.
  1. How did you handle replicates?
  • In this dataset, there are 3 biological replicates for each condition. From the box and density plots before normalization, I don’t think there are any outlier. The replicates didn’t variate a lot.
  1. What is the final coverage of your dataset?
  • I got 15159 genes left after cleaning. So the final coverage of the data is around 61% - 76%.
